{"title_page": "Wrestling World 2000", "text_new": "{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name=Wrestling World 2000\n|image=File:Chris_Benoit_in_the_Ring.jpg\n|caption=[[Chris Benoit]], who portrayed his former [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]] \"Wild Pegasus\" at the event.\n|promotion=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]\n|date={{dts|2000|1|4}}<ref name=Jan4-00>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome.html#0100 | title= Wrestling World 2000 | date= January 4, 2000 | accessdate= April 13, 2010 | publisher= ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref>\n|venue=[[Tokyo Dome]]\n|city=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|attendance=53,500<ref name=Jan4-00/>\n|liveevent=N\n|event= [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show|Wrestling World]]\n|lastevent2=[[Wrestling World 1999|1999]]\n|nextevent2=[[Wrestling World 2001|2001]]\n}}\n'''Wrestling World 2000''' was a [[professional wrestling]] event produced by [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW). It took place on January 4, 2000 in the [[Tokyo Dome]]. Wrestling World 2000 was the ninth [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] held by NJPW. The show drew 53,500 spectators and $5,900,000 in ticket sales.<ref name=Jan4-00/> The event saw the return of [[World Championship Wrestling]]'s [[Chris Benoit]] under the [[ring name]] Wild Pegasus, reprising the character he played for NJPW in the early to mid-1990s. The show also featured [[Rick Steiner]] and [[Randy Savage]], both working as freelancers brought in specifically for the show. The twelve match card saw a successful defense of the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]] and the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship]] as well as [[Kensuke Sasaki]] defeating [[Genichiro Tenryu]] to win the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]]. The undercard featured a match between [[Masahiro Chono]] defeated [[Keiji Mutoh]] bearing a stipulation that the losing wrestler's faction would have to disband. Chono represented Team 2000, while Mutoh represented [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo Japan]]. Through Mutoh's loss nWo Japan ceased to be. It also featured the retirement match of [[Kazuo Yamazaki]], as he wrestled his student, [[Yuji Nagata]].\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nThe [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] is NJPW's biggest [[List of NJPW pay-per-view events|annual event]] and has been called \"the largest professional wrestling show in the world outside of the United States\" and the \"Japanese equivalent to the [[Super Bowl]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?40241 | title = GFW News: New Japan Pro Wrestling \"Wrestle Kingdom 9\" press conference details | date=December 23, 2014 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net}}</ref><ref name=WK11AXSPWT>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/13/new-japans-wrestlekingdom-11-air-axs-tv-starting-jan-13-four-weekly-special-episodes-ross-barnett-commentary/ | title = New Japan's WrestleKingdom 11 to air on AXS TV starting Jan. 13 in four weekly special episodes with Ross & Barnett on commentary | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=December 13, 2016 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> \n\n===Storylines===\nWrestling World 2000 featured [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and [[Narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in scripted events that built tension and culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm | title = How Pro Wrestling Works | last=Grabianowski | first=Ed | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=HowStuffWorks, Inc. | publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=\n|times=<ref name=Jan4-00/>\n|match1=[[Shinjiro Otani]] and [[Tatsuhito Takaiwa]] (c) defeated [[Kendo Kashin]] and [[Minoru Tanaka (wrestler)|Minoru Tanaka]]\n|stip1=[[Tag team]] match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]]\n|time1=13:19\n|match2=[[Shiro Koshinaka]] defeated [[Satoshi Kojima]]\n|stip2=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time2=10:17\n|match3=[[Hiroyoshi Tenzan]] defeated [[Chris Benoit|Wild Pegasus]]\n|stip3=Singles match\n|time3=10:55\n|match4=[[Jushin Thunder Liger]] (c) defeated [[Koji Kanemoto]]\n|stip4=Singles match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time4=03:56\n|match5=[[Manabu Nakanishi]] defeated [[Kenzo Suzuki]]\n|stip5=Singles match\n|time5=06:41\n|match6=[[Yuji Nagata]] defeated [[Kazuo Yamazaki]]\n|stip6=Singles match\n|time6=06:44\n|match7=[[Kimo Leopoldo|Kimo]] defeated [[Kazuyuki Fujita]] by disqualification\n|stip7=Singles match\n|time7=04:02\n|match8=[[Scott Norton]] defeated [[Don Frye]]\n|stip8=Singles match\n|time8=08:50\n|match9=[[Rick Steiner]] defeated [[Randy Savage]]\n|stip9=Singles match\n|time9=11:08\n|match10=[[Shinya Hashimoto]] and [[Takashi Iizuka]] defeated [[Kazunari Murakami]] and [[Naoya Ogawa]]\n|stip10=Tag team match\n|time10=11:29\n|match11=[[Masahiro Chono]] defeated [[Keiji Mutoh]]\n|stip11=Singles match; with Mutoh losing, [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo Japan]] was forced to disband\n|time11=25:00\n|match12=[[Kensuke Sasaki]] defeated [[Genichiro Tenryu]] (c)\n|stip12=Singles match for the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time12=14:43\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.njpw.co.jp/ NJPW.co.jp] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling events|January 4 Tokyo Dome Show}}\n\n[[Category:2000 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:2000 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:January 2000 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:January 4 Tokyo Dome Show|2000]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name=Wrestling World 2000\n|image=File:Chris_Benoit_in_the_Ring.jpg\n|caption=[[Chris Benoit]], who portrayed his former [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]] \"Wild Pegasus\" at the event.\n|promotion=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]\n|date={{dts|2000|1|4}}<ref name=Jan4-00>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/tokyodome.html#0100 | title= Wrestling World 2000 | date= January 4, 2000 | accessdate= April 13, 2010 | publisher= ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref>\n|venue=[[Tokyo Dome]]\n|city=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|attendance=53,500<ref name=Jan4-00/>\n|liveevent=N\n|event= [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show|Wrestling World]]\n|lastevent2=[[Wrestling World 1999|1999]]\n|nextevent2=[[Wrestling World 2001|2001]]\n}}\n'''Wrestling World 2000''' was a [[professional wrestling]] event produced by [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW). It took place on January 4, 2000 in the [[Tokyo Dome]]. Wrestling World 2000 was the ninth [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] held by NJPW. The show drew 53,500 spectators and $5,900,000 in ticket sales.<ref name=Jan4-00/> The event saw the return of [[World Championship Wrestling]]'s [[Chris Benoit]] under the [[ring name]] Wild Pegasus, reprising the character he played for NJPW in the early to mid-1990s. The show also featured [[Rick Steiner]] and [[Randy Savage]], both working as freelancers brought in specifically for the show. The twelve match card saw a successful defense of the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]] and the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Championship]] as well as [[Kensuke Sasaki]] defeating [[Genichiro Tenryu]] to win the [[IWGP Heavyweight Championship]]. The undercard featured a match between [[Masahiro Chono]] defeated [[Keiji Mutoh]] bearing a stipulation that the losing wrestler's faction would have to disband. Chono represented Team 2000, while Mutoh represented [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo Japan]]. Through Mutoh's loss nWo Japan ceased to be. It also featured the retirement match of [[Kazuo Yamazaki]], as he wrestled his student, [[Yuji Nagata]].\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nThe [[January 4 Tokyo Dome Show]] is NJPW's biggest [[List of NJPW pay-per-view events|annual event]] and has been called \"the largest professional wrestling show in the world outside of the United States\" and the \"Japanese equivalent to the [[Super Bowl]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?40241 | title = GFW News: New Japan Pro Wrestling \"Wrestle Kingdom 9\" press conference details | date=December 23, 2014 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net}}</ref><ref name=WK11AXSPWT>{{cite web | url = http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/12/13/new-japans-wrestlekingdom-11-air-axs-tv-starting-jan-13-four-weekly-special-episodes-ross-barnett-commentary/ | title = New Japan's WrestleKingdom 11 to air on AXS TV starting Jan. 13 in four weekly special episodes with Ross & Barnett on commentary | last=Keller | first=Wade | authorlink=Wade Keller | date=December 13, 2016 | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> \n\n===Storylines===\nWrestling World 2000 featured [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] that involved different wrestlers from pre-existing scripted feuds and [[Narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers portrayed [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villains]], [[Face (professional wrestling)|heroes]], or [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#tweener|less distinguishable characters]] in scripted events that built tension and culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm | title = How Pro Wrestling Works | last=Grabianowski | first=Ed | accessdate=October 9, 2017 | work=HowStuffWorks, Inc. | publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=\n|times=<ref name=Jan4-00/>\n|match1=[[Shinjiro Otani]] and [[