{"title_page": "Tripleman\u00eda VIII", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 Lucha Libre AAA World Wide event}}\n{{Infobox wrestling event\n|name=Tripleman\u00eda VIII\n|image=TriplemaniaVIII.jpg\n|caption=The TV logo used when the show was broadcast on television with both the Mexican and the Japanese flag shown\n|promotion=[[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]]\n|date=July 5, 2000<ref name=\"Trip8\">{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/mexico/aaa/triple.html#viii | title = Asistencia Asesor\u00eda y Administraci\u00f3n TripleMan\u00eda | accessdate = 2009-02-19| publisher = ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref>\n|attendance=1,700<ref name=\"Trip8\"/>\n|venue=[[Korakuen Hall]]<ref name=\"Trip8\"/>\n|city=[[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]]<ref name=\"Trip8\"/>\n|lastevent=[[Rey de Reyes (2000)|Rey de Reyes]]\n|nextevent  = [[Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo (2000)|Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo]]\n|event=[[Tripleman\u00eda]]\n|lastevent2=[[Tripleman\u00eda VII|VII]]\n|nextevent2=[[Tripleman\u00eda IX|IX]]\n}}\n'''Tripleman\u00eda VIII''' was the eighth [[Tripleman\u00eda]] [[professional wrestling]] show promoted by [[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]]. The show took place on July 5, 2000 in [[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]]. It was only the second show to take place outside Mexico and the first show to take place in Japan. The Main event featured an [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Trios rules (Relevos Australianos)|Eight-man \"At\u00f3micos\" tag team match]] which saw AAA regulars team up with various Japanese wrestlers. The team of [[Octag\u00f3n]], [[Jushin Thunder Liger]], [[Latin Lover (wrestler)|Latin Lover]], and [[El Alebrije (wrestler)|El Alebrije]] took on [[Cibern\u00e9tico]], [[Nobuhiko Oshima|Shiima Nobunaga]], [[Abismo Negro]], and [[Electroshock (wrestler)|Electroshock]].\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nIn early 1992 [[Antonio Pe\u00f1a]] was working as a booker and storyline writer for [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL), Mexico's largest and the world's oldest wrestling promotion, and was frustrated by CMLL's very conservative approach to ''[[lucha libre]]''. He joined forced with a number of younger, very talented wrestlers who felt like CMLL was not giving them the recognition they deserved and decided to split from CMLL to create [[Asistencia Asesor\u00eda y Administraci\u00f3n]], later simply known as \"AAA\" or Triple A. After making a deal with the ''Televisa'' television network AAA held their first show in April 1992.<ref name=SLOrbit>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/el-fin-de-una-era/| title= El fin de una era| date= October 7, 2006 | accessdate= October 14, 2009 | author= Ocampo, Ernesto | publisher=[[Super Luchas]] | language=Spanish}}</ref> The following year Pe\u00f1a and AAA held their first [[Tripleman\u00eda]] event, building it into an annual event that would become AAA's [[Super Bowl]] event, similar to the [[WWE]]'s [[WrestleMania]] being the biggest show of the year.<ref>{{cite book|author=Madigan, Dan|title=Mondo Lucha Libre: the bizarre and honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling|publisher=HarperColins Publisher|year=2007|chapter=A family affair|pages=128\u2013132|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> The 2000 Tripleman\u00eda was the eight year in a row AAA held a Tripleman\u00eda show and the fifteenth overall show under the Tripleman\u00eda banner.\n\n===Storylines===\nThe Tripleman\u00eda VIII show featured six [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[Screenplay|scripted]] feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plots]] and [[narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers were portrayed as either [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heels]] (referred to as ''rudos'' in Mexico, those that portray the \"bad guys\") or [[Face (professional wrestling)|faces]] (''t\u00e9cnicos'' in Mexico, the \"good guy\" characters) as they followed a series of tension-building events, which culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.\n\n==Reception==\nJohn F. Molinaro from the Canoe.ca website wrote that the Tripleman\u00eda show that kicked off the tour was well received by the crowd.<ref name=Canoe2000/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe rest of the AAA tour of Japan drew very low attendance figures, drawing only 409 in [[Nagoya]] and 507 in [[Kobe]] for the next two stops of the tour as AAA failed to gain the interest of the Japanese fans even by bringing in several well known Japanese wrestlers.<ref name=Canoe2000>{{cite web | url=http://www.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingInternational/mexico_topten.html | title=2000 Year in Review - Mexico | first=John F. | last=Molinaro | accessdate=July 31, 2015 | work=Slam Wrestling! | publisher=Canoe.ca}}</ref> AAA had plans to do further tours in Japan in 2001 but after drawing such low interest they dropped the plans for regular tours.<ref name=Canoe2000/> AAA only made brief tours of Japan since then, teaming up with a Japanese promotion for the tours.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=8&nr=122&page=8&name=&vDay=&vMonth=&vYear=&showtype=&location=&arena=&region=Asien | title=Asistencia Asesoria y Administracion (AAA) Region: Asia | accessdate=August 1, 2015 | publisher=Cagematch}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=\"Trip8\"/><ref name=Lucha2000>{{cite news|title=2000 Especial!|work=Box y Lucha Magazine|pages=2\u201328|id=issue 2488|date=January 9, 2001|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|hide=all\n|match1=[[Octagoncito (AAA)|Octag\u00f3ncito]] defeated [[Mini Abismo Negro]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=04:38\n\n|match2=[[Gran Apache]] defeated [[El \u00c1ngel (wrestler)|\u00d3scar Sevilla]]\n|stip2=Singles Match\n|time2=11:04\n\n|match3=[[El Oriental]] and [[Esther Moreno]] wrestled [[Pentag\u00f3n]] and [[X\u00f3chitl Hamada]] to a double count out\n|stip3=[[Tag team|Tag team match]]\n|time3=12:14\n\n|match4=[[Perro Aguayo Jr.]], [[El Alebrije (wrestler)|El Alebrije]], and [[Dark Ozz|Pathfinder]] defeated ''Los Vatos Locos'' ([[El Picudo]], [[Charly Manson]] and [[Esp\u00edritu (wrestler)|Esp\u00edritu]]), ''Team Japan'' ([[Naomichi Marufuji]], [[Minoru Tanaka (wrestler)|Minoru Tanaka]] and [[Genki Horiguchi]]) and ''[[Los Vipers]]'' ([[Histeria (wrestler)|Histeria]], [[Psicosis II|Psicosis]] and [[Maniaco]])\n*Perro Aguayo, Jr. pinned Charly Manson.\n*Naomichi Marufuji pinned Histeria.\n*Perro Aguayo, Jr. pinned Genki Horiguchi\n|stip4=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Basic elimination matches|Four corners elimination match]]\n|time4=12:33\n\n|match5=[[Heavy Metal (wrestler)|Heavy Metal]] and [[Tiger Mask IV]] defeated Kick Boxer and [[Yoshinobu Kanemaru]]\n|stip5=Tag Team match\n|time5=13:21\n\n|match6=[[Octag\u00f3n]], [[Jushin Thunder Liger]], [[Latin Lover (wrestler)|Latin Lover]], and [[Hector Garza]] defeated [[Cibern\u00e9tico]], [[Nobuhiko Oshima|Shiima Nobunaga]], [[Abismo Negro]], and [[Electroshock (wrestler)|Electroshock]]\n|stip6=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Trios rules (Relevos Australianos)|Eight-man \"At\u00f3micos\" tag team match]]<ref name=TMWinners>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/2009/05/29/los-grandes-ganadores-de-triplemania/ | title=Los grandes ganadores de Triplemania | first=Alex G | last=Ruiz | work=SuperLuchas Magazine | date=May 29, 2009 | accessdate=July 11, 2015 | language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|time6=13:01\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.luchalibreaaa.com/eventos-magnos/triplemania/item/93-tripleman%C3%ADa-viii-la-internacionalizaci%C3%B3n-total.html Tripleman\u00eda VIII at LuchaLibreAAA.com]\n\n{{AAAPPV|Tripleman\u00eda}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Triplemania 08}}\n[[Category:2000 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:Tripleman\u00eda]]\n[[Category:Events in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:2000 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:July 2000 events in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2000 Lucha Libre AAA World Wide event}}\n{{Infobox wrestling event\n|name=Tripleman\u00eda VIII\n|image=TriplemaniaVIII.jpg\n|caption=The TV logo used when the show was broadcast on television with both the Mexican and the Japanese flag shown\n|promotion=[[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]]\n|date=July 5, 2000<ref name=\"Trip8\">{{cite web | url = http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/mexico/aaa/triple.html#viii | title = Asistencia Asesor\u00eda y Administraci\u00f3n TripleMan\u00eda | accessdate = 2009-02-19| publisher = ProWrestlingHistory.com}}</ref>\n|attendance=1,700<ref name=\"Trip8\"/>\n|venue=[[Korakuen Hall]]<ref name=\"Trip8\"/>\n|city=[[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]]<ref name=\"Trip8\"/>\n|lastevent=[[Rey de Reyes (2000)|Rey de Reyes]]\n|nextevent  = [[Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo (2000)|Verano de Esc\u00e1ndalo]]\n|event=[[Tripleman\u00eda]]\n|lastevent2=[[Tripleman\u00eda VII|VII]]\n|nextevent2=[[Tripleman\u00eda IX|IX]]\n}}\n'''Tripleman\u00eda VIII''' was the eighth [[Tripleman\u00eda]] [[professional wrestling]] show promoted by [[Lucha Libre AAA World Wide|AAA]]. The show took place on July 5, 2000 in [[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]]. It was only the second show to take place outside Mexico and the first show to take place in Japan. The Main event featured an [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Trios rules (Relevos Australianos)|Eight-man \"At\u00f3micos\" tag team match]] which saw AAA regulars team up with various Japanese wrestlers. The team of [[Octag\u00f3n]], [[Jushin Thunder Liger]], [[Latin Lover (wrestler)|Latin Lover]], and [[El Alebrije (wrestler)|El Alebrije]] took on [[Cibern\u00e9tico]], [[Nobuhiko Oshima|Shiima Nobunaga]], [[Abismo Negro]], and [[Electroshock (wrestler)|Electroshock]].\n\n==Production==\n===Background===\nIn early 1992 [[Antonio Pe\u00f1a]] was working as a booker and storyline writer for [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL), Mexico's largest and the world's oldest wrestling promotion, and was frustrated by CMLL's very conservative approach to ''[[lucha libre]]''. He joined forced with a number of younger, very talented wrestlers who felt like CMLL was not giving them the recognition they deserved and decided to split from CMLL to create [[Asistencia Asesor\u00eda y Administraci\u00f3n]], later simply known as \"AAA\" or Triple A. After making a deal with the ''Televisa'' television network AAA held their first show in April 1992.<ref name=SLOrbit>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/el-fin-de-una-era/| title= El fin de una era| date= October 7, 2006 | accessdate= October 14, 2009 | author= Ocampo, Ernesto | publisher=[[Super Luchas]] | language=Spanish}}</ref> The following year Pe\u00f1a and AAA held their first [[Tripleman\u00eda]] event, building it into an annual event that would become AAA's [[Super Bowl]] event, similar to the [[WWE]]'s [[WrestleMania]] being the biggest show of the year.<ref>{{cite book|author=Madigan, Dan|title=Mondo Lucha Libre: the bizarre and honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling|publisher=HarperColins Publisher|year=2007|chapter=A family affair|pages=128\u2013132|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> The 2000 Tripleman\u00eda was the eight year in a row AAA held a Tripleman\u00eda show and the fifteenth overall show under the Tripleman\u00eda banner.\n\n===Storylines===\nThe Tripleman\u00eda VIII show featured six [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[Screenplay|scripted]] feuds, [[plot (narrative)|plots]] and [[narrative thread|storylines]]. Wrestlers were portrayed as either [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heels]] (referred to as ''rudos'' in Mexico, those that portray the \"bad guys\") or [[Face (professional wrestling)|faces]] (''t\u00e9cnicos'' in Mexico, the \"good guy\" characters) as they followed a series of tension-building events, which culminated in a wrestling match or series of matches.\n\n==Reception==\nJohn F. Molinaro from the Canoe.ca website wrote that the Tripleman\u00eda show that kicked off the tour was well received by the crowd.<ref name=Canoe2000/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe rest of the AAA tour of Japan drew very low attendance figures, drawing only 409 in [[Nagoya]] and 507 in [[Kobe]] for the next two stops of the tour as AAA failed to gain the interest of the Japanese fans even by bringing in several well known Japanese wrestlers.<ref name=Canoe2000>{{cite web | url=http://www.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingInternational/mexico_topten.html | title=2000 Year in Review - Mexico | first=John F. | last=Molinaro | accessdate=July 31, 2015 | work=Slam Wrestling! | publisher=Canoe.ca}}</ref> AAA had plans to do further tours in Japan in 2001 but after drawing such low interest they dropped the plans for regular tours.<ref name=Canoe2000/> AAA only made brief tours of Japan since then, teaming up with a Japanese promotion for the tours.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=8&nr=122&page=8&name=&vDay=&vMonth=&vYear=&showtype=&location=&arena=&region=Asien | title=Asistencia Asesoria y Administracion (AAA) Region: Asia | accessdate=August 1, 2015 | publisher=Cagematch}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=\"Trip8\"/><ref name=Lucha2000>{{cite news|title=2000 Especial!|work=Box y Lucha Magazine|pages=2\u201328|id=issue 2488|date=January 9, 2001|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|hide=all\n|match1=[[Octagoncito (AAA)|Octag\u00f3ncito]] defeated [[Mini Abismo Negro]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=04:38\n\n|match2=[[Gran Apache]] defeated [[El \u00c1ngel (wrestler)|\u00d3scar Sevilla]]\n|stip2=Singles Match\n|time2=11:04\n\n|match3=[[El Oriental]] and [[Esther Moreno]] wrestled [[Pentag\u00f3n]] and [[X\u00f3chitl Hamada]] to a double count out\n|stip3=[[Tag team|Tag team match]]\n|time3=12:14\n\n|match4=[[Perro Aguayo Jr.]], [[El Alebrije (wrestler)|El Alebrije]], and [[Dark Ozz|Pathfinder]] defeated ''Los Vatos Locos'' ([[El Picudo]], [[Charly Manson]] and [[Esp\u00edritu (wrestler)|Esp\u00edritu]]), ''Team Japan'' ([[Naomichi Marufuji]], [[Minoru Tanaka (wrestler)|Minoru Tanaka]] and [[Genki Horiguchi]]) and ''[[Los Vipers]]'' ([[Histeria (wrestler)|Histeria]], [[Psicosis II|Psicosis]] and [[Maniaco]])\n*Perro Aguayo, Jr. pinned Charly Manson.\n*Naomichi Marufuji pinned Histeria.\n*Perro Aguayo, Jr. pinned Genki Horiguchi\n|stip4=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Basic elimination matches|Four corners elimination match]]\n|time4=12:33\n\n|match5=[[Heavy Metal (wrestler)|Heavy Metal]] and [[Tiger Mask IV]] defeated Kick Boxer and [[Yoshinobu Kanemaru]]\n|stip5=Tag Team match\n|time5=13:21\n\n|match6=[[Octag\u00f3n]], [[Jushin Thunder Liger]], [[Latin Lover (wrestler)|Latin Lover]], and [[Hector Garza]] defeated [[Cibern\u00e9tico]], [[Nobuhiko Oshima|Shiima Nobunaga]], [[Abismo Negro]], and [[Electroshock (wrestler)|Electroshock]]\n|stip6=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Trios rules (Relevos Australianos)|Eight-man \"At\u00f3micos\" tag team match]]<ref name=TMWinners>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/2009/05/29/los-grandes-ganadores-de-triplemania/ | title=Los grandes ganadores de Triplemania | first=Alex G | last=Ruiz | work=SuperLuchas Magazine | date=May 29, 2009 | accessdate=July 11, 2015 | language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|time6=13:01\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.luchalibreaaa.com/eventos-magnos/triplemania/item/93-tripleman%C3%ADa-viii-la-internacionalizaci%C3%B3n-total.html Tripleman\u00eda VIII at LuchaLibreAAA.com]\n\n{{AAAPPV|Tripleman\u00eda}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Triplemania 08}}\n[[Category:2000 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:Tripleman\u00eda]]\n[[Category:Events in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:2000 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:July 2000 events in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wi